{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_hatra_ver01/data/sn86091197/00279550973/1924040301/0547.xml":{"full_text":"I\nOur Farm Bureau Page\nEdited by the County Agent\nFARM CONVENTION\nAT TWIN\nFALLS\nAt a farmers' convention at Twin\nFalls the best available speakers\nwere put forth to advise how to\nhandle the crops anS stock this 'year\n\n\nThere is sufficient water to grow j\nfeed crops necessary to keep j\nIdaho livestock up to full produc- j\ntlon, according to the report of the j\nfirst agricultural economic confer-j\nence held at Twin Falls, March 21\nand 22, and in addition, some cash j\ncrops can be produced at good pro-1\nfits on short water rations. The con- I\nference stressed the Importance of I\nprotecting investments in livestock\nby keeping up maximum production\nand further emphasized the planting\nJ\nThe first Idaho agricultural\nto make the most of the water\nshortage that is bound to be with us,\nand we reprint the following from\nthe Pocatello Tribune:\nour\nof crops needing little Irrigation,\nnomic conference was called by W.\nKjosness, state leader of county\nagents. County agents met on these\ndates to consider the threatening\nwater shortage and what crops to\ngrow under the present market and\nmoisture conditions Represents\ntivp\u00ab Of Farmer\u00ab' Connerative Mar\nketing association, the State Bank\ners' association. Irrigation Projects\nand federal and state specialists\njoined the county agents in their\ndpHheraHnns\nR. L. Spangler, assistant agrono\nmist of the University of Idaho ex\ntension division, and Julius Jacob\nson, United States crop and livestock\nstatistician for Idaho, made the prin\ncipal contributions of information\naffecting the present situation. Mr.\nSpangler spoke on the irrigation re\nquirement of crops, storage water\nsupplies, precipitation and moisture\ncontent of soils. Mr. Jacobson re\nported on the condition of crops, in\ntended plantings by farmers and\nholdover stocks for the world,\nUnited States, western states and\nIdaho. He also reviewed the favor\nable conditions presented to the\nIdaho farmer thru the increasing\npopulation in California and the\nwidespreading\nCalifornia and neighboring states.\nThe essential features of the confer\nence recommendations follows:\nthruout\ndrought\nlivestock\nIn making plans affecting the live\nstock business, it is well to remem\nber that butter, as compared to other\ncommodities, has a purchasing\npower of 112, eggs 121, wool 145;\nthat beef prices have been steadily\ncoming up; that, in the past, such\nperiods as this of heavy pork pro\nduction and low prices have led to\nreduction in breeding so drastic as\nto result later on in shortage and\nindications are that hog producers\nmay now be moving into one of the\nrecurrent periods of low production.\nLivestock husbandry has always\nbeen the keystone source of income\nof Idaho irrigated farmers. It is well\nto remind ourselves that Idaho farm\ners have right now an investment of\n>10,644,000 in dairy cows. >13,318,\n000 in beef cattle, >21.291,000 in\nsheep, >3,553,000 in hogs and >7,\n000,000 in producing hens.\nNo estimates are available for the\ninvestment in livestock equipment.\nWise farmers and bankers are giv\ning first consideration to the main\ntenance to full production of dairy\ncows, poultry, sheep, beef cattle and\nhogs by planning cropping systems\nwhich will furnish ample feed. They\nrecognize the danger of great loss\nunless the great investment in live\nstock and equipment is protected by\nproduction to full capacity. Unless\nfeeds are abundant, many farmers\nmay be required to sell high priced\nlivestock at a great sacrifice.\nThe growing of feed crops for\nlivestock is, therefore, regarded as\nof the first importance. Cash crops\nshould receive secondary considera\ntion because of the small investment\nwhich they carry at present and be\ncause of the greater risk attached to\nthe production and marketing of\nsuch crops.\nGrain Crops\nOf all the grain crops barley re\nquires the least amount of irrigation\nto mature. It is the first ranking\ngrain feed for livestock for Idaho.\nNext to barley, oats requires the\nleast amount of water and Its im\nportance is growing out young stuff\ncommends it as a crop in short water\nyears. Corn has become the basic\nfattening feed for lamb, steer and\nhog feeding. It can be produced\nwith much less water than most\nfarmers use and it will mature much\nbetter without the last Irrigation,\nwhich most farmers apply. It re\nquires, however, a late Irrigation\nand storage water should be the\ndomin\u00e2t factor in determining\nrequires more water than barley or\noats.\nForage Crops\nAlfalfa may be compared to corn\nin irrigated requirement. Corn for\nsilage, however, requires less water\nthan corp for mature grain. For a\npasture, sweet clover requires less\nwater and produces more pasture\nthan any other grass. Pasture plant\nings are dangerous in short water\nyears because of the risk in securing\na good stand.\nCultivated Crow\nBeans require the least amount of\nwater of all the cultivated crops.\nNext to beans comes peas, then po\ntatoes. Onions and beets are safe\ncrops to plant where there is ample\nstorage water for a late irrigation.\nIn connection with cash crops, we\ndesire to call attention to the report\nof the United States division of crop\nand livestock estlmaes relative to\nprobable plantings and coupled with\nthis, the increase in shipments of\nIdaho cash crops to California mar\nkets due to steadily Increasing popu\nlation. In view of the prevailing\ndrought in California, the outlook is\nfor Increased consumption of Idaho\nproducts.\nSeed Crops\nIt requires less water to produce\nalfalfa seed than it does for either\nIt is safe to at\n\nseed peas or clover.\ntempt clover seed production where\na late irrigation is assured. Seed\npeas require less Irrigation than\nclover and about the same amount\nas wheat. In short w'ater years ex\nperienced seed growers have saved\njj le fi rs t crop of alfalfa or clover for\nsee( j an< j only good clean fields,\nth\u00ae same as that presented in 1919.\ne have this advantage, however,\nexperience has taught us the better\nuse \u00b0t irrigation water, both early\nan d late runoff, and storage supplies,\nWe can pretty accurately estimate\nl\u00b0 r each individual project how early\nand how late storage water must be\nU8\nWater Supplies\nThe situation as to water is about\nh f 0 xperl3nCe \u00b0h 19 19, kTI\nea n goo d practice to hold\ns ucb of the ear overflow of the\nS ?ake by running it into the canals\nth n upper Snake F lver va e r and\nth V s the .\u00cf\" 4 underground reser\nvolr there This underground reser-1\nI voir water gets back into the Snake\nriver later in the season and\nI caught as_ a late season runoff on the\n1( ?y er irrigation projects. This en\nabI f s the conservation of storage\nwater with better promise of late\nirrigation this year than in 1919.\nPrecipitation has been closer to\normal to tbe south than towards\ntne moun tains.\nMarch and April\nmay improve the fall in the mount\nains. At present, however, the frost\nis out of almost of the farming sec-,\nlions. The content of moisture in\nseed beds seems to be above that of\n1919. The ground is in excellent\ncondition for plowing and early seed\ning. Wise farmers are at work early\nand late and attach the harrow to\nthe plow to cut off evaporation.\nThe conference has faith in the\nexperience of project managers and\ntheir understanding of the irrigation\nrequirements of crops and the profit\nable and efficient use of storage\nwater this season is important. Idaho\nirrigated farmers can go thru an\nother year of successful production\nif willing co-operation is extended\nproject managers.\n\nDAIRY COWS HELPED\nSeventy-five dollars an acre was\nthe annual gross income on the farm\nof George Smithers and his two sons\nof Wood county, Ohio, in 1923, and\nof that amount more than half came\nfrom the herd of purebred Holsteins,\naccording to an account in a recent\nissue of the Ohio Farmer.\nFor several years Mr. Smithers and\nhis boys milked grade Holsteins and\ndetailed their milk in the little city\nof Rossford. After getting some\nvaluable experience with grades,\nthey embarked into the purebred\nbusiness.\nPractically all the feed required\nby their cows is grown on the farm.\nOf the 120 acres cultivated, about\ntwenty-four were in alfalfa last year.\nSoybeans are put in the corn for sil\nage. With such roughage along\nwith corn and oats, the feed problem\nis solved, except for test cows for\nwhich only oil meal need be bought.\nSugar beets are also available.\nThe Smithers by no means carry\nall their eggs in one basket. The\nHolsteins last year brought about\n>3000 in milk shipped to Toledo and\n>2500 in cattle sales. In addition,\n220 apples trees returned about\n>1500; tomatoes, >1200; beets for\nthe nearby sugar company, >1000;\npoultry about >500; and the rest of\nthe year's sales came from wheat,\ncorn and hay\u2014a grand total of\n>10,750 for the year, besides what\nthe farm contributed to the support\nof three families.\nWhat these Ohio farmers have\ndone on high priced land can be\nduplicated anywhere where hay and\ngrain is grown. There is always a\nmarket for dairy products and the\nincome is sure and regular at all\nseasons of the year.\nA POULTRY PASTURE\nBy C. B. Ablson, Field Agronomist\nand State Seed Commissioner\nBesides being an extraordinary\nlegume for dairy pasture, Ladino\nclover, a giant white clover, has\ngiven excellent satisfaction among\npoultry men who use this forage\ncrop as green feed for chickens.\nCows, sheep, hogs and horses also\nrelish this clover more than any\nother legume.\nIt is especially well adapted to the\nirrigated sections. It responds\nreadily to the application of water\nand starts growing exceptionally\nin the and, with\nattention, continues to grow late\ninto the fall.\nThe members of the Ladino Seed\nGrowers association. Filer, are sold\nto the merits of this crop. Further\ntests, are being conducted thruout\nIdaho, Oregon and Washington, on\nthe value of this legume as a pasture\nfor livestock, especially dairy cows.\nThe seed is rapidly being disposed of\nfor permanent pasture purposes.\nThe growers have found that the\nbest results are obtained by plant\ning three to five pounds per acre\nwithout a nurse crop. The first\nthree weeks is the critical time and\nthe plants should not be allowed to\nsuffer from want of water during\nthat period.\n\nHardest Substance.\nThe hardest substance known is\nprobably the diamond, and the next\ncarborundum. The softest metal la\nmercury and the next potassium. Of\nthe more common metals lead Is prob\nably the softest with gold next. Gold\nU probably the most malleable metal\nand silver next.\nLETTER FROM MR. MOORE\nThe following letter has just been\nreceived from Mr. Moore regarding\nthe relative value of white or colored\neggs. Many inquiries have been re\nceived at this office for this informa\ntion;\nMr. Walter F. Thomas,\nCounty Agricultural Agent,\nBlackfoot, Idaho.\nDear Mr. Thomas;\n\ni\nj\n\nThis is in reply to your letter of\nthe 17in inst., asking as to the rela-j\ntive value of white and brown eggs\nas they sell on the general markets\ni\nThe chalk white transparent full j\nand sweet egg, weighing an average\nof 24 ounces to the dozen and with j\nno egg in a case weighing less than j\n22 ounces to the dozen, is the high\nest priced egg on the market thru\nany system employed for marketing i\nthem. New York sets the standard\nof the country.\nstates are known as brown-sheHed\negg consuming states and Boston\nparticular, but white eggs are going\nonto that market now very satis\nfactorily. Thru the association,\nhowever, we are often able to make\nbrown shells bring as much as\nwhites, but generally speaking, the\nwhite shelled egg brings more\nfor market eggs and other markets\nconform to it. The New England\nmoney.\nVery truly yours,\nPREN MOORE,\nState Poultry Specialist\n\u2022h\n_\nr J he call me a scrub rooster! Yet\ni ba e a pe ,j lg T ee I was sired by a\nf crub,dam d by a scrub and\ntreated like a scrub, and I sometimes\nhat 1 am wned by a BC b\ny ribe outnumbers good roosters\nfive one Just why I exist is a\nmystery even to me. Yet I am not\nfesponsible for it. I was brought\n,nt T thiB orld \"l th ut m L con8en \u00ee\nand I shall probably leave it against\nmy wil1 In th \u2122e antime J. am\ngetti ng vlcloas publicity,\nPrincipally thru the poultry and farm\nP r ss They say I am a renegade\nand an abomination, and should be\nexterminated. Poultrymen passing\nmy owner s farm look at me with\ncontempt, even the hens show me no\nrespect. My own daughters seem to\nhold a grude against me, saying that\nI am responsible for their low egg\nproduction. I cannot argue the\npoint, because it is true. But what\ncan I do? My owner must think a\nlot of me personally, or he would not\ncontinue to support me, knowing\nthat I can never improve the quality\nof his flock or be a source of profit\nto him. Trap nest records are cer\ntainly showing me up and I can see\nthe handwriting on the wall. My\ntribe is doomed! Under the keen\ncompetition and reasonable prices of\npedigreed roosters there is no place\non the farm for me. So goodbye, I\nmay be gone, but not forgotten, for\nI have retarded the development of\nthe poultry industry, for lo, these\nI MEDITATIONS OF\nA SCRUB ROOSTER\nam\nmany years.\nWith apologies to Dorman,\nR. V. MITCHELL.\n\nREPORT ON\nPOULTRY ASSOCIATION\nIn a recent issue we stated that a\ntotal of 68,000 hens had been signed\nup for the Egg Marketing associa\ntion. The following letter shows an\nerror on our part, there being only\n60,000 at the present time:\nDear Mr. Thomas;\nThe contracts seem to be in from\nall the counties, so far as we know\nwe only have about 60,000.\nhave taken the matter up with the\nboard of directors of the Idaho\nOregon Egg Producer's association\nat Caldwell and they are of the\nopinion that we had better extend the\ncampaign for thirty days more, and\nin their Judgment it would not be\nadvisable to attempt to set up a\nbranch office in this section of the\nstate with less than 75,000 hens.\nIt will be impossible to conduct\nan active campaign from Pocatello,\nhowever, we will take care of the\ndetail work that might be entailed\nduring the next thirty days.\nThe question of whether we will\nhave an egg marketing association\nin this part of the state is wholly up\nto the growers. If they do not\nshow interest enough to sign np an\nother 15,000 bens, a candling sta\ntion will not become a reality in\nthis part of the state.\nI wish you would write me fully\nand advise me if your people desire\nto make further efforts to complete\nthe sign-up.\nWe\nYours truly,\nC. BEN ROSS.\n\nInscribed Stone Under Lava.\nMiners working more than 200 feet\nbeneath nn old lava flow at Columbia.\nCal., found an irregularly-shaped gran\nite tablet on which queer hieroglyphics\nwere carved. Evidently the carvings,\nwhich were regular in form, date from\nprehistoric times. Scientists are trying\nto decipher them.\n0RETHR0AT\nS\ntonsilitis or hoarseness,\ngargle with warm salt\nwater. Rub Vicks over\nthroat and cover with a\nhot flannel cloth. Swal\nlow slowly small pieces.\nVICKS\nw VapoRul\nOw tT UiBi m m Jmn U\u2014d Ytarh,\n4\n4\nMORELAND\n\ni\nReceived March 31\nFeed grinding and seed cleaning,\nPotato\nadv. 14-15\nsatisfaction guaranteed,\nGrowers Association.\nMrs. Laura Wray returned from\nPocatello during the week. She\nwent to visit her daughter, Mrs.\nGlenn Foreman.\nJoseph Fyance was a visitor In Po\ncatello during the week.\nEdward Benson has bought the\nRalph Robins place and Chester\nGrimmltt has bought the Benson\nborne.\nMr. and Mrs. Virgie McBride have\nmoved on to the Robin's home and\nwill help Mr.\" Benson for the coming\nseason.\nRelief society was held Tuesday,\nMoreland during the week\nMiss Edna McKnight entertained\nthe girls of the 1. W. and W. club\nj on Wednesday evening. A nice\nlunch was served, and all present\nthejhad a splendid time,\ni\n\nMrs. Clark and Mrs. Dance of the\nstake board were visitors.\nMrs. Griddle of Idaho Falls was in\nI A number of our young folks\nwent to Blackfoot to attend the\nI American Legion concert Thrusday\nj evening.\nI Ray McMillen went to Pocatello to\nI take part in the contest in public\nI speaking.\nMr. and Mrs. Chancy Christensen\nI were visitors in Riverside Wednes\nday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Earl Furnice were\nin Blackfoot on business the last of\nthe\ntheir\nJohn Wray went to Pocatello\nSaturday to see his daughter,\nElice Harten met with a sad acci\n(j en j when he fell and bruised his\nf ace quite badly, caused by heart\nfailure.\nMr. and Mrs. Bingham spent the\nwee k-end in Blackfoot.\nMiss Lola Grieves spent Sunday in\nPocatello visiting with friends,\nMrs. Wright, who has just re\nturned from a visit to California\nwith her sons, was here and spent a\nj ew (jays with her daughter and\nf am iiy.\nMr. and Mrs. Ray Bagster spent\nthe week-end in Blackfoot shopping,\nthe week.\nMrs. Homer Carter^ spent\nweek-end with her parents.\nMr. and Mrs. Thomas Richardson\nand son Doyal, of Hamer, Idaho,\nwere here visiting with Mrs. Mc\nKnight the last of the week.\nThe eighth grade held\nmonthly social in the school house\non Saturday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Frank Brown, of\nPocatello were visitors at the Fyance\nhome Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Abe- Scott, of Rich,\nwere guests of Mr. and Mrs. Orson\nWest.\nOliver McBride left Monday for\nLost River to work for the coming\nseason.\nMr. and Mrs. Vardey McNeil spent\nSunday with Mrs. Oliver McBride.\nMrs. Anna Jorden and children\nleft for Pocatello Saturday to visit\nher daughter Mrs. Richardson for a\nfew days.\nVJ\n\u2022.v.\nWhy do women like\nOakland's automatic\nspark control so well?\ntv\n[a]\ny\nBecause there is no spark\nlever for them to operate,\nand none is needed.\n!f\n\nAndren Auto Co.\nBlackfoot, Idaho\nTrue Blue\nj\\\n\n0\n\u2022V\nX\nHi\nHi\n'.V,\nLO]\nf\n\n1\n1\n\nfe.&S\ni Mm\nMV\nS;\nJr\n\nmm\n\niSiSSUcr.\nwag h m\niiSm\nid\n\nff\nWater Shortage Predicted\n\nThose men who are predicting a short\nage of water for the coming season should\nnot be called pessimists, neither should\nthey be called prophets. They should be\ntermed clear thinking, farsighted men. We\nshould profit by their warning by prepar\ning to conserve the spring moisture.\nOur Land Roller or Pulverizer is a\nmighty good tool for this purpose.\nWe should buy what we need before\nbuying what we want and let good tools\nhelp us to hasten the return of prosperity.\nTHE BISTL1NE COMPANY\nMcCormick-Deering Line of Farm\nMachinery\nMrs. Lettie Hale returned to Po\ncatello, after a visit with her sister,\nMrs. Hazel Lindsay.\nMrs. A1 Benson spent the week\nend in Blackfoot.\n\u2022K\n\n\nPINGREE\n\n\n1 satisfaction^\n1 Growers Association,\n\u2022r\nReceived March 31\nPeed grinding and seed cleaning,\nguaranteed.\nPotato\nadv. 14-15\nj here Friday night,\nMrs. V. J. Larson \u00eeoox her baby\nj to Aberdeen Tuesday, where she had\nan absess lanced on the baby's arm.\nj Mr. and Mrs. Delbert Packer and\nj family attended the show at Thomas\nSaturday night.\nMiss Bernie Morgan spent the\nweek-end visiting in Blackfoot.\nThe geneological committee took\ncharge of the L. D. S. services Sun\nday.\nA good crowd attended the dance\n\nR. E. Porter took his wife to Po\ncatello Friday, March 21, where she\nwas operated on Saturday for ap\npendicitis. She is getting along very\nnicely at this time.\nThose who attended the show at\nSterling Thursday were Mr. and\nMrs. A. L. Carlile, Miss Fern, Viola\nand Rilla Carlile, Virgie Packer, Ab\nide Hellen and Fay Caldwell, Grace\nWeaver, Mrs. Dora Pugmire and\nOral Carlile.\nArchie Grimmett spent the week\nend at Moreland.\nThe musical program given by the\nM. I. A. Sunday evening was very\nwell attended and very much en\njoyed.\nMrs. E. S. Buchanan has returned\nhome from visiting in Utah.\nMrs. Fred Snapp is on the sick list\nthis week.\nMary Hlgby has been visiting rela\ntives in Blackfoot the past week.\nVirgie Packer went to Blackfoot\nFriday to take part in the spelling\ncontest.\nJ. H. Weaver attended the funeral\nof his brother Horace, at Mont\npelier.\nMrs. Alex Heide went to Blackfoot\nlast week.\nMr. Bartlett and M. C. Cool made\na business trip to Arco Monday and\nwill remain several days.\nTony Cerroni and family left Mon\nday for Toelle, Utah, where they in\ntend to make their home.\nHenry Mara has returned from\nToelle, Utah, where he has been\nworking this winter.\n\nTTTTTTT*|\nCENTERVILLE\n\nI\" \"I\"!\u2014\u00bb\u2014I*\nv\nReceived March 31\nFeed grinding and seed cleaning,\nguaranteed.\nPotato\nadv. 14-15\nMr. and Mrs. E. S. Deardorff and\ndaughter were guests to dinner at\nthe Stone home Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. C. E. Haynes and\nfamily called at the Garlic home Fri\nday evening.\nHarry Killion is listed among the\nsick this week.\nMrs. Joe Tressl and sons Joe and\nCharlie called on William Arvish in\nBlackfoot Saturday.\nMr. and Mrs. C. E. Haynes and\nfamily, Mr. and Mrs. Butch Tressl\nand Charlie Tressl spent Sunday\nevening at the Addie Tressl home.\nRuby Clark, of Moreland, visited\nEdna Fay Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. C. I. Stone visited\nWednesday at the Joe Tressl home.\nMr. and Mrs. Joe Fay and family\nvisited at the Brown home Sunday.\nMrs. Theo Farnworth and baby\nvisited in Centerville Thursday. She\nleft for Twin Falls the first of the\nweek, where Mr. Farnworth is work\ning.\nsatisfaction\nGrowers Association.\n4\nGeneral Auctioneers\nGraduate of the\nMissouri Auction School\nLet me sell your property\nfor more money. Ring the\nRepublican office, phone 45.\nSeverin Johnson","height":"20496","width":"14544"}}
